# History: hephaestus-env-var-fallback-path-resolution

Newest-first archive of prior versions. Each entry records version, date,
what changed, why, and a full snapshot of the previous version's body.

---

## v1.0.0 → v1.1.0 (archived 2026-06-12)

**What changed:** Added a new failure mode and the headline verification-fidelity
lesson: in a git worktree with an editable install (PEP 660), a
`Path(__file__)`-anchored repo-root walk-up resolver (`.git` OR `pyproject.toml`
marker, first-match-up) can silently resolve to the PARENT meta-repo (or a sibling
checkout that also has the marker file), making a checker read the WRONG file and
report PASS even on injected-violation input. Documented the
`python -m pkg.mod` invocation as the robust fix (vs `python path/to/shim.py`),
added the probe/diagnostic recipe, and added five Failed Attempts rows. Bumped
`verification` from `verified-local` to `verified-ci` (deps/version-sync passed in
CI). Added `history` frontmatter field.

**Why:** ProjectHephaestus issue #1181 / PR #1266 surfaced this as a real bug —
a version-single-source checker passed locally even with an injected
`[project].version` violation because repo-root resolution read the parent
meta-repo's pyproject.toml, not the worktree's. The existing skill already owns
"robust repo-root resolution across editable installs / CI / worktrees," so this
is the correct place for the new failure mode and the lesson that local
verification of `__file__`-anchored tooling run inside a worktree is untrustworthy.

